title: what happens when debounce.maxWait is triggered?
body:
Hey hi, I am trying to understand a behavior in my app that may be related to how maxWait in debounce is handled.

Basically I am debouncing keystrokes on an input and in some rare cases the last keystroke will never be catched.

Options used:

``` js
debounce(inputCallback, 100, {
  leading: true,
  maxWait: 200,
  trailing: true
});
```

While using those options (lodash 3), is there a possibility that the last keystroke is not triggered and trailing: true is not working as I thought?

A suite of events:
- t0: keystroke 1
- t0+25ms: keystroke 2
- t0+200ms: keystroke 3
- t0+220ms: keystroke 4

It seems that I only get keystroke 1 and keystroke 3

While I would have thought I would get keystroke 1, 3 and 4 (trailing: true).

The bug in my app (not getting the last keystroke) is hard to trigger/track so maybe you have a pointer here?

If I do not use maxWait then everything is fine.

title: Re-state purposes of _.tap and _.thru in docs
body:
`_.thru` seems like a better recommendation for _altering_ intermediate results in a chain, and `_.tap` for _triggering side-effects_ based on the intermediate results (console.log, fs write, etc).

The only way `_.tap` can change the intermediate values in the chain is by mutative side-effects, which isn't something to be encouraged, IMO.

title: Lodash breaks when transpiled twice
body:
Original issue: https://github.com/rackt/redux/pull/611#issuecomment-177625155

Basically we started using Lodash as a dependency of Redux, and I noticed that UMD builds can no longer be tested from our Mocha tests. After more investigation I realized that they break _if they are transpiled twice_ because Babel inserts `use strict` in the code, and then Lodash `function () {return this;}` global detection returns `undefined`.

I'm not sure whether this can be considered a Lodash issue. Definitely transpiling twice is wrong but some people do that due to bad configurations. We used to support transpiling twice, but now due to our new dependency on Lodash, transpiling twice is broken.

What do you think?

title: Alias omit to unset in FP
body:
I realize that `omit` is already aliased to `dissoc`, but currently lodash/fp's `unset` is not immutable, which is surprising and arguably incorrect for an FP method.

You could make `unset` immutable, but then it would be useless to return a boolean, so it might as well just be overwritten by `omit` to provide the same functionality as `dissoc`. Then it would pair more sensibly with `set`, which currently _is_ immutable.

title: Alias set to assoc in FP
lodash/fp alias set to assoc?
body: Lodash/fp aliases `omit` to `dissoc`, so it's kind of surprising that it doesn't alias `set` to `assoc`.

This is not really an issue, more a question on reasons behind a breaking change done in v4.

Convenience for you? (easier to code / to maintain / to test / whatever)

title: v3 _.pick vs v4 _.pickBy removed key field
body:
The following in v3 works:

`_.pick({ foo: 'bar', baz: 'brrr' }, function(val, key) { return key === 'foo'; });`
gives: {foo: "bar"}

But the same in v4 using _.pickBy() doesn work

`_.pickBy({ foo: 'bar', baz: 'brrr' }, function(val, key) { return key === 'foo'; });`
gives: {}

The callback in _.pickBy only provide the value, but not the key from the object your picking from. Is this intended? The above use case can be solved in a different way, but it's still a surprising breaking change which doesn't seem to be documented.

title: .value() breaking change in lodash 4.0.1
Too many changes are NOT backwards compatible!
body:
I am not sure what philosophy you guys are after, but upgrading to v4 should not require project re-writes across the board. I do understand that new features and optimizations are necessary but they come at a very high price!

Here are some examples where migration script did not do jack.

lodash v.3.1

``` js
_.each(this.files, function(file){...});
```

lodash v.4

``` js
_.each(this.files, _.bind( function(file){...} )); //have to use _.bind to keep the context
```

Another idea, once methods are introduced and adopted, please DO NOT change their behavior. You can add additional functionality, but do not take it away. Example __.functions_ was returning all methods in a scope ( including the ones on the prototype ) .... now it only returns the immediate methods. THIS BREAKS STUFF. _So please do not take away existing functionality_ 

Changes like that should NOT be necessary when upgrading!

title: Since v4 defaultsDeep converts function property into object
suggestion: _.hasDuplicates
body:
I often want to use a function that should be called `_.hasDuplicates`, which means

```
_.hasDuplicates([1, 2, 3]) // false
_.hasDuplicates([1, 2, 2]) // true
_.hasDuplicates([1, -1, 2], Math.abs) // true
```

lodash already has `_.uniq` so it can be written as `array.length !== _.uniq(array).length`, but it is a little difficult to read and has some extra calculations. 

I often use it to validate request parameters.
`const isValid = _.isArray(arr) && _.every(arr, _.isString) && !_.hasDuplicates(arr);`

I would be glad if you think about it.

First of all, thank you for you absolutely amazing dedication to this project. For quite a while now this is the one library that my projects most heavily depend on. Please keep up the great work!

My issue:

I just switched to the new 4.0.0 release. Pre 4.0.0 I used variations of this shorthand a lot:

`_.chain(...).filter(RegExp.prototype.test, /abc/)`

Basically, being able to filter/reject etc strings in an array based on a regexp. In 4.0.0 this no longer works (also not with the _.matchesProperty shorthand)

I haven't really seen the above shorthand documented that often so its use is probably a bit hacky.

Does the 4.0.0 release support a similar shorthand?

Thanks!

title: Adding prod method
body:
numpy has a method called prod, which is to calculate prod of each element.
It is similar to _.sum except that prod multiplies elements instead of adding them.
Here is an example:

```
>>> np.prod([1, 2, 3])
6
```

Here is the document:
http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.10.0/reference/generated/numpy.prod.html

I created this issue because having this feature is consistent with sum method.

Redundant comparison in the new toInteger function?
body:
Looking at the new toInteger function in lodash 4.0, I see the following comparison at line:

```
return value === value ? (remainder ? value - remainder : value) : 0;
```

It looks to me as it could be simplified as

```
return remainder ? value - remainder : value
```

Or I'm missing something?

title: _.templateSettings with node.5.4.1 npm 3.5.2
body:
Hi,
I have just hat a encountered a problem with `._.templateSettings`

We are using node `5.4.1` and npm `3.5.2` and it seems that npm now shares dependencies (seems to use the same instance) with the same version of different modules.

example:
we are using lodash `3.10.0`
and a dependant module also uses lodash `3.10.0`

this means that both `require("lodash")` seem to reference the same instance because when we change the `._.templateSettings` property it also effects the dependant modules lodash and because that module is also using `_.template` it throws syntax errors and stops working.

I know that this is not really a bug of lodash but I would like to bring this issue to the table because the usage of `_.templateSettings`seems rather dangerous to me and this should maybe be mentioned in the docs. 

I am also thinking about raising an issue for npm because I imagine that this could be a problem in other situations too..

Hopefully my concern is clear..
Regards

title: lodash/fp's get -> prop aliasing is broken
body:
73405cf incorrectly fixed #1755. `get` should be aliased to `prop` and `path` because its overloaded getter argument satisfies the interface of both -- `prop` takes a string and `path` takes an array.

`property` shouldn't be aliased to anything, because it doesn't curry.

title: lodash 4 overwrites global `_` variable even when browserified
body:
Lodash v4 overwrites the global `_` variable even when browserified.

This caused issues for me because I have an application which depends on the global `_` being Lodash v3, and one of my browserified dependencies updated to depend on Lodash v4 recently.

I see from https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/1798 that this looks intentional, but I'm still unclear how I can make a module/library like https://github.com/AgentME/contain-by-screen use lodash v4 without having it overwrite the global `_`.

I can't have my library call `_.noConflict()` on the Lodash object, because if the application is also using Lodash v4, then `require('lodash')` in the library will get me the same instance of Lodash that the application is using and unset the global that it might be depending on. (Also, if the library had multiple entry points that could be required, then all of them that required lodash would each have to remember to call `_.noConflict()`.)

title: 'pickBy' incompatible with 3.x 'pick'
`pad*()` will fail to padding if the string tailing with `\0`
body:
``` javascript
const _ = require('lodash');

const buf = new Buffer([49, 50, 51, 52, 0, 0, 0, 0]);
const str = buf.toString('utf8');

console.log('[' + str + ']');
console.log('[' + _.padEnd(str, 7) + ']');
```

Like the above code, the string is converted from buffer with `\0` padding on the end, and the output is:

``` javascript
[1234]
[1234]
```

It failed to padding as the converted string contains `\u0000` as part of the string, although it's not visible. The correct result should be:

``` javascript
[1234]
[1234   ]
```

The problem was raised in Node.js project nodejs/node#4775, however, they thought `\u0000` should be part of the string. In that case, I think the lodash might need to handle those invisible characters in Unicode, including `\u0000`, so the padding can be corrected.
